article.description: Tangela Smith scored 21 points and the Sting rallied to beat the Lynx 81-68.
article.headline: Sting spoil Lynx interim coach Jenkins' home debut
article.linkText: Sting spoil Lynx interim coach Jenkins' home debut
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Charlotte forward Tangela Smith put an eight-point game in a home loss to Minnesota behind her in a hurry.

Smith scored 21 points and Sheri Sam added 17 to help the Sting beat the Lynx 81-68 on Thursday night. The Sting (8-18), who lost to Minnesota at home on Tuesday night, had a 15-4 advantage in offensive rebounds.

"We have been trying to emphasize the turnovers as well as the offensive rebounds, and tonight we came out and limited them to one opportunity and took care of the basketball," Sting coach Muggsy Bogues said. "That was a key factor for us."

Seimone Augustus scored 19 points for the Lynx (9-16) in interim head coach Carolyn Jenkins' first loss. Jenkins took over when Suzie McConnell Serio resigned Sunday and won her first game, 70-62 in Charlotte.

"We showed some signs of life and had some spark, but when you're playing a team twice in a week, they're going to remember what you did to them before," Jenkins said. "We're still focusing on what we have to do defensively, and that's not going to happen
overnight."

Trailing by three at the half, the Sting went on a 15-2 run to open up a 10-point lead early in the third. Augustus capped an 8-0 run to knot it at 64 in the fourth quarter, but Smith had nine points in the final four minutes as the Sting pulled away.

"They kept fighting throughout the whole game, but we stuck together as a team and just fought harder than they did at the end," Smith said. "It was a very physical game inside and outside. Nobody wanted to lose tonight, but the team that played the most aggressive came away with a win."

Vanessa Hayden added 17 points and nine rebounds for the Lynx. She was also called for a flagrant foul with 1:04 to play for elbowing Helen Darling in the face.

"You have to give them credit, but also say we made some mental breakdowns," Hayden said. "I got a flagrant. That definitely helped the pace of the game. It's something that gave them fire and took something out of us."

Paced by Smith's eight first-half points, the Sting led by as many as six in the opening 20 minutes before Minnesota ended the half on a 12-3 run for a 39-36 advantage at the break. Augustus and Hayden each had 10 points in the first half for the Lynx.

Sam was called for a technical foul in the first quarter and officials mistakenly gave Augustus two free throws. She made both, but one point was taken off the board later in the quarter when the error was realized.
